What’s actually happening (mechanically)

You’ve got three things combining:

1. Thermal advantage
    Panels trap a bit of heat → warm, stable microclimate
2. Predator shielding
    Hawks, owls, even cats can’t get under there easily
3. Structural grip + access path
    The panel frame turns a slick roof into something climbable and navigable

→ Result: you accidentally installed a squirrel condo.

⸻

The real risk (this is the part people miss)

This goes beyond just “annoying animals”:

* Wire damage → they love chewing insulation
* Fire risk → exposed wiring + dry nest material
* Panel efficiency drop → airflow gets blocked
* Long-term repeat occupation → once one family uses it, others follow

⸻

What actually fixes it (properly)

Not removal alone—you need denial of re-entry:

* Install a critter guard / wire mesh skirt around the entire panel perimeter
* Make sure it’s:
    * Tight enough to block entry
    * Ventilated enough to not trap heat

Important sequence:

1. Confirm no babies are inside (season matters)
2. Evict (humane methods if needed)
3. Seal immediately (or they’ll be back within days)

